\f0\fs30 \cf2 1
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:22.130
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Are there any stories you remember that your parents or grandparents told you that happened to your family during the Genocide?
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 2
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:00:22.150 --> 00:01:04.230
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Of course. My grandfather told us a lot that during the killings in Turkey he had already been a soldier for 9 years. He'd been shot in the eye, so he had one eye only. I was a small child when he told me this, but I remember till now that they got to Syria, Aleppo with a lot suffering and hardship. And like that he would tell me stories that I remember until today.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 3
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:01:04.250 --> 00:01:08.850
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Do you know what town or village they were from?
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 4
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:01:08.870 --> 00:01:11.820
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Marash.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 5
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:26.830
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Were there other stories about how they came to Aleppo or what happened during the deportation?
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 6
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:01:26.850 --> 00:01:37.870
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 I do not remember how they arrived in Aleppo, but I know they had to walk barefoot to Aleppo.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 7
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:01:37.890 --> 00:01:56.560
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 They got scared and fled barefoot. My grandfather's brother was also with him at that time. I do not remember how old my father would have been, but I think he must have been 1 or 2 or 3. Or maybe he was born in Aleppo? I do not remember.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 8
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:01:56.580 --> 00:02:18.590
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 And then when they came to Aleppo, do you know what difficulties they faced rebuilding their life in Aleppo.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 9
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:02:18.610 --> 00:03:10.060
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 My grandfather worked at a cotton factory. They paid with gold then, there was no money yet. They brought a few pieces of gold, bought a house and continued their lives. My father was a woodworker, he made furniture. We had our own house and that is where he worked. \'a0My uncle went to Brazil. My family just kept going on. My father got married, etc.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 10
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:03:10.080 --> 00:03:19.980
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 When you grew up, did you live in the same house and which neighborhood was that in?
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 11
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:31.570
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Yes, yes. In the Nor Kiugh neighborhood. I also took up my father's craft.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 12
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:03:31.590 --> 00:03:49.690
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Can you describe a little bit what it was like growing up in Nor Gyugh? What school you went to, what activities you did?
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 13
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:03:49.710 --> 00:04:08.960
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 I went to Mesrobian school till the 6th grade, then I learned my father's craft. My father needed my help. We were three sons. My other brothers practiced other crafts, and I worked with my father.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 14
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:04:08.980 --> 00:04:27.350
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 We went to the Armenian community club. I entered Armenian political organization life, and lived on. I grew up, went to the army and served for 3.5 years there. When I came back my father died. He was sick.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 15
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:04:27.370 --> 00:04:49.000
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 When you left school to work, was that your decision or you had wanted to do or your father told you to start working?
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 16
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:04:49.020 --> 00:05:12.490
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 My father worked at home and he needed help. A carpenter needs an assistant, doesn't he? There was no worker then to help him and it was tiring. So I had to leave school and learn the craft.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 17
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:05:12.510 --> 00:05:21.300
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Did you enjoy working with your father and learning from him carpentry?
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 18
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:05:21.320 --> 00:05:25.600
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Of course, Of course.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 19
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:05:25.620 --> 00:05:45.860
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 When you went to the Army, was that something...can you talk about that experience? Was it difficult, did you have a lot of friends that were also going?
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 20
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:05:45.880 --> 00:06:16.420
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 One makes many friends in the army. The young men in our neighborhood also served in the army--we were together in different places. Military service is a good thing. A young man should serve in the army to in order to know the meaning of life and the value of his parents.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 21
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:53.060
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Serving in the army teaches a young man many things: first of all, respect. \'a0It builds character. It teaches you to respect both young and old. That is what a soldier learns. Thank God, Our parents raised us that way even before we went to the army. So when we went to the army, they would see how respectful we were, and we'd enter the officer's cabinet. They'd know that we knew how to respect others and that' we'd been brought up well.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 22
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:06:53.080 --> 00:07:15.510
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Before the Army, when you were living in Nor Gyugh were you interacting mostly with Armenians or also non-Armenians?
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 23
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:07:15.530 --> 00:07:43.130
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 At that time, there were only maybe 1-2 Arab families. The rest were Armenians. On every road, there were houses next to each other with yards connecting the neighbors. There were about 2 or 3 Muslim families I think. Further up there were more, but our area only had 2 or 3.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 24
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:07:43.150 --> 00:08:07.200
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Of course we had markets where people from the villages came to get vegetables, including Armenians. But essentially, everyone was Armenian. There were also a few Kurds. And Arabs. But the majority was Armenians. There were no apartment buildings, only houses with yards.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 25
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:08:07.220 --> 00:08:25.110
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 At that time did you feel Armenian or Syrian or a mix of both?
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 26
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:08:25.130 --> 00:09:11.150
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 First off, Armenian. Then, it goes without saying, if you were born in Syria, you're also a Syrian. We went to school, and we've known since childhood that we have a motherland, Armenia. We've learned songs since that time. The children that are born and raised here, most do not know the songs that we used to sing. We've known since childhood that we have a motherland, Armenia, Armenian relatives, and we are Armenians--we felt Armenian.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 27
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:09:11.170 --> 00:09:35.650
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 When you went to the Army did that change how you felt about being Syrian at all or was it hard to be around not as many Armenians?
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 28
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:09:35.670 --> 00:10:24.720
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 No, no, never. In those years, when I went to the army, there would always be Armenians in the barracks. Always, at least more than one. They knew that you were Armenian. The leaders of the barracks were well-disposed towards Armenians because Armenians are considered reliable. Of course there were Armenians, and we never felt like an alien in the army; there was no discrimination between Muslims or Kurds or Armenians. We were Armenian and there was absolutely no discrimination against anyone. They never said anything like "Oh he is Armenian, or he is this or that." Never.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 29
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:10:24.740 --> 00:10:43.130
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Can you describe your life after the Army. So, coming back to Nor Gyugh, if you started work or a family?
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 30
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:10:43.150 --> 00:11:21.490
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 After I returned from the army, well before I finished my time in the army, my father died. I had a workshop, my own workshop. I was a little depressed over my father's early death. I couldn't work for a year. Then I realized things couldn't go on that way. Everyone would say, why don't you start a shop and work, etc. etc.? 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 31
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:11:21.510 --> 00:11:31.960
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 So, I began to work later and for a long while, 10 years, I did the same job.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 32
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:11:31.980 --> 00:12:03.200
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 I had some accidents. I came to Armenia in 1991. I wanted to see my homeland and visit my relatives. I came to look around and loved it to the level that I was here for three months but it felt like three days.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 33
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:12:03.220 --> 00:12:38.610
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 I'd met many people who'd been to Aleppo. Everything was great. Well, the circumstances were hard, but that was a good time. Then it became a little difficult. I came back to Armenia in 1992 and got engaged. Then, in 1993, I came and got married. Later, I went back to Aleppo after I got married in 1993 and I didn't come back here for 20 years.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 34
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:12:38.630 --> 00:13:09.600
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 I would send my wife to Armenia and later children to Armenia. Their grandparents and my aunt lived here. 20 years later, I said let me go see how my motherland was doing. It was good, and I noticed many changes. I'd inquire from those who'd visit Armenia and they'd tell me what the streets were like now. I had known the streets by heart before.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 35
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:13:09.620 --> 00:13:35.250
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 When I came, I was surprised, many things had changed in Armenia, the city had changed entirely. There's everything here. However, unfortunately, the people have regressed in their opinion of outsiders.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 36
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:13:35.270 --> 00:14:26.110
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 It is difficult for us to understand this. In Syria, when we see a foreigner, we rush to help. We think, "The man is from Armenia, has come down from Armenia." We've helped many people like that.. Unfortunately, I have not seen that here. Not even with acquaintances or close relatives. My wife's father is my mother's cousin. They migrated here in 1946. [1]
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 37
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:14:26.130 --> 00:14:34.900
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 We had problems later. An accident, too...
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 38
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:14:34.920 --> 00:14:59.710
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 When you first came to Armenia, the time when you met your wife, did you ever think of moving here or you've always knew you wanted go back to Aleppo?
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 39
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:14:59.730 --> 00:15:16.430
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 In 2000-2001 many friends and acquaintances of mine would visit Armenia and see the changes. They praised Armenia. They encouraged me to go see the country myself.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 40
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:15:16.450 --> 00:15:41.750
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 At this point, I had dropped my father's craft, and started to work in the culinary field. They'd tell me that I would do really well in Armenian because there was no Syrian cuisine in Armenia. I told my wife I wanted to sell the house, go to Armenia and open a place there. Her parents were there, etc.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 41
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:15:41.770 --> 00:15:53.190
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 She said she didn't want to go back to Armenia. My wife was born and raised in Armenia and said she didn't want to go to Armenia. So we stayed in Aleppo.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 42
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:15:53.210 --> 00:16:17.610
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Later, in 2010, a close friend of mine, a dentist, told me to go to Armenia for a trip. He told me to go. He said there were food places opening Armenia and doing well there. 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 43
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:16:17.630 --> 00:16:55.220
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 He said there were two restaurants of our type of cuisines--one Lebanese, and a friend of ours, Koko, had opened another in 2000. He said go see for yourself, maybe you'll decide to move there. I came here and looked around at the end of 2010. I came and I loved it here. I even worked here for a week, with our type of cuisine not theirs. 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 44
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:16:55.240 --> 00:17:14.200
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 I thought I might move here and work here. My children were still small, and I thought they could grow up in an Armenian environment. They were at ease in Aleppo, but I wanted them to grow up in Armenia, in their motherland.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 45
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:17:14.220 --> 00:17:31.960
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 They were small and quick to learn. They speak the language well with a good accent. I decided to move here. This was before the war.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 46
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:17:31.980 --> 00:17:51.050
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 How was it for your wife resettling in Aleppo when she moved back. It sounds like she really liked the life there?
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 47
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:17:51.070 --> 00:18:25.740
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 Before we were married, she had visited Aleppo. I got her a visa. She's the daughter of my mother's cousin. So I got her father and her a visa for them to come and see Aleppo. She came and loved it there. And were not strange to each other. We were related. Her father and my mother are cousins. We liked each other, and we both said ok.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 48
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:18:25.760 --> 00:18:42.130
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 So, we got married in 1993, came to Aleppo and it was not like a foreign land to her. We lived with understanding, but when we came here, problems began.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 49
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 00:18:42.150 --> 00:19:57.730
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs30 So we moved here. Things were fine for about a year. We had work and were glad. My brother-in-law worked as a driver for someone. They had a place. He knew that I was a cook, and so he offered to start a restaurant together. I agreed. I went to Aleppo, and brought goods back with me. I was the first person to open a food place with our cuisine in Armenia. My wife is a cook, too. Many say, \'93Oh, but your wife is from Armenia.\'94 But she learned to cook in Aleppo from my mother, and my aunt. My wife cooks very well.
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs30 \cf2 50
